==English==
===Etymology===
Latin [[diapason]], from Greek [[διαπασων]], that is [[δια]] [[πασων]] ([[χορδων]]) ‘through all (notes)’.

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /dʌɪə'peɪzən/

===Noun===
'''diapason'''
# the [[range]] or [[scope]] of something, especially of [[note]]s in a [[scale]], or of a particular musical [[instrument]]
#:*'''1934''': the piano curving like a conch, corollas giving out '''diapasons''' of light — Henry Miller, ''Tropic of Cancer''


